        <description>As they entered they saw <person>Dorian Gray</person>. He was seated at the piano, with his back to them, turning over the pages of a volume of Schumann’s “Forest Scenes.” “You must lend me these, <person>Basil</person>,” he cried. “I want to learn them. They are perfectly charming.”</description>
    </paragraph>

    <paragraph>
        <description>“That entirely depends on how you sit to-day, <person>Dorian</person>.”</description>
    </paragraph>

    <paragraph>
        <description>“Oh, I am tired of sitting, and I don’t want a life-sized portrait of myself,” answered the lad, swinging round on the music-stool in a wilful, petulant manner. When he caught sight of <person>Lord Henry</person>, a faint blush coloured his cheeks for a moment, and he started up. “I beg your pardon, <person>Basil</person>, but I didn’t know you had any one with you.”</description>
